= The witness itself is within awareness


Again, sort of the same topic about this witnessing of thoughts. Starting up with the cognitive diffusion as they call it in cognitive science, and they call unbinding and dharma. And so it starts by witnessing thoughts, right? We can just know that, wow, I'm really stuck on this topic, or I'm lost in some kind of worry, or some kind of fear, some desire. This occupies the mind, and believe it or not, it's that simple.

We start out, we don't really see that we're being autopiloted. It's a kind of an involuntary thing where we... it's like we're sitting on a roller coaster ride. Yeah, we're there, but we're getting taken for a ride. And a lot of the times the thoughts are encouraged by nefarious outer places, you know---powerful propaganda machines and sense stimulations and enticing, enticing ways to just grab the mind, many ways now.

So it starts by just witnessing thoughts; and we go back to that method that we have where we purposefully bring up a thought. So, if you want to do the 10 minute meditations, you can lie down, sit, even stand or walk. But if you're going to sit, then you have a posture that starts to come to you naturally. You start to find a posture. It means your hand mudras and your legs, everything, you start to find a comfort there. And then even when you're walking, you start to find a more naturalness. But anyway so, in the 10 minute sessions, we can just leave the eyes open and like powering off a car engine, you're just letting be. Even all these weird feelings, and what are the... they call them idiosyncrasies... I don't know if that's the right word, but little things, right? Little feelings, emotions, thoughts, but just letting them be here without modifying, without holding anything.

And that allows that returning to what they call the natural state in Dzogchen. So in 10 minutes with the eyes open just being here with the energy of your experience. You can start witnessing the thought, we'll say "The dog's ear is itchy." We'll have that thought "The dog's ear is itchy." And we just look: where, where's the mind that's having that thought? "The dog's ear is itchy."

Now, let's go mono-cognitive for a second. Let that be the only thought you're having. And if you feel resistance to this, it's good to release that resistance and give it a try. Set your mind completely blank like a whiteboard or something, and then we're going to have this thought. You might as well add "the loud dog's ears itchy"... no, no, no, let's keep it at "The dog's ears itchy." So, we have a blank canvas. No thoughts. Ready? "The dog's ears itchy." And it appears within this awareness, right?

This, your mind holding that thought, that's the power right there. It's so simple-they say this everywhere. It's right in front of you. That's called this meta awareness, metacognition, Buddha nature. This is the secret, this very simple mind that holds that thought. And now instead of "The dog's ears itchy" and that taking me away for a ride---cuz remember it could be, oh I'm hungry for some pizza or something, you know, and we just go for it---but now you're in your meta awareness, the nature of your mind. Now you can...

[Talking to dogs] "Hey, come here. Hey..." Hold on a second... "You guys are determined to accumulate negative karma right now."

So yes, it starts by just witnessing a thought because that is the burden of so many beings, right? They ending their lives, they're on drugs, they're chasing, chasing, chasing because some thoughts are dragging them around. And I think the sad part about that is many times these aren't thoughts that we would willingly get hooked on. Smoking and drinking are great examples of us being hooked into thoughts that we don't even want, right? 

And then our minds are so tender and vulnerable and susceptible that we start getting cultural thoughts in our head without even knowing it. Next thing you know: who's thinking? Who's the one... who am I? You know. Beginning to witness them is the first step to diffusion, to unbinding. Then you start to get a little free will. Well, I don't want to follow that thought, or I want to let this go because this thought keeps making me sad. We all know that if we think about certain topics, it makes us sad. Now, if they come up naturally, of course, it's fine.

So, any questions about that? The witness and witnessing thoughts. So far, I think many of you know that. 

Okay, and then the witness itself of course is also within awareness. The feeling of me sitting here right now. You can use awareness and look: "Who is the one thinking right now?" "Who is the one hearing me?" Let that open up. Mhm. That's the egoic construct, that contraction into a conditioned self, the witness.

So you have three aspects. You have the witness bound to thoughts within awareness to create our stress and suffering. Then we unbind... and free.
Making sense? Perfect sense, right? All right, any questions about that? And everybody got it, yeah? That's the key to meditation, all right everybody. 

Okay. Well, that's all I have to say about that. Just revisiting old topics, I suppose. And then if everybody's going to be so quiet right now, we'll just go to the text. You are just having a lot of meditation in your life.

Yeah, and a thought starts to diversify, so at first we have a thought "The dog's ear is itchy." This is a linguistic cognitive pattern. We have emotional cognitive patterns too. And then we have things like self grasping or self contraction, which is also a pattern, right? And so it's a kind of thought, it's an act of consciousness. It feels like "I'm sitting here aware of the thought." The... I was going to call him the lion, he is a lion, but "The dog's ear is itchy." I'm having that thought. It feels like there's an apprehension there, right? Anyone not relating to that by the way? It starts to become pretty apparent within awareness. So these are just kind of the phases out of our troubled mind. Go ahead, yes.

